00:10:46.896 --> 00:10:49.266
asking yourself, and to me,

00:10:49.266 --> 00:10:51.406
quality is all about care.

00:10:52.096 --> 00:10:53.846
So when I heard care connected

00:10:53.846 --> 00:10:55.496
to quality not only from that

00:10:55.496 --> 00:10:57.006
clip we just heard from Travis,

00:10:57.556 --> 00:10:59.306
but it also came up in my

00:10:59.306 --> 00:11:00.326
interview with Gary.

00:11:01.636 --> 00:11:03.576
>> If it's quality, it's better

00:11:03.576 --> 00:11:04.536
than something that's not

00:11:04.536 --> 00:11:06.156
quality by virtue of someone

00:11:06.156 --> 00:11:07.086
caring about it.

00:11:07.796 --> 00:11:10.616
>> Right. I totally agree that

00:11:10.666 --> 00:11:11.976
caring makes things better.

00:11:12.706 --> 00:11:14.476
For example, I care about this

00:11:14.476 --> 00:11:16.676
presentation, so, naturally,

00:11:16.676 --> 00:11:18.216
it's just a little bit better

00:11:18.216 --> 00:11:19.676
than if I didn't care about it

00:11:19.676 --> 00:11:19.946
at all.

00:11:20.646 --> 00:11:22.726
So now, I feel like we should

00:11:22.726 --> 00:11:24.966
dig into, what is care?

00:11:26.076 --> 00:11:27.306
Okay, we're going to stick with

00:11:27.306 --> 00:11:28.896
a few interview clips from Gary

00:11:28.896 --> 00:11:30.726
so you can hear more of the full

00:11:30.726 --> 00:11:31.576
conversation.

00:11:32.116 --> 00:11:34.286
So I asked him, "How would you

00:11:34.286 --> 00:11:35.716
describe care?"

00:11:36.256 --> 00:11:40.896
>> Just that someone, excuse my

00:11:40.896 --> 00:11:42.886
French, gave a [beep].

00:11:44.096 --> 00:11:44.796
>> [laughter] I'm not sure if

00:11:44.796 --> 00:11:46.436
that's a WWDC first, but it's

00:11:46.436 --> 00:11:47.016
simple.

00:11:47.156 --> 00:11:47.826
I like it.

00:11:48.976 --> 00:11:49.706
[laughs] Really, what he's

00:11:49.706 --> 00:11:52.596
saying here is that care is a

00:11:52.596 --> 00:11:53.316
motivator.

00:11:53.886 --> 00:11:56.666
So how do you look at care in

00:11:56.666 --> 00:11:57.196
design?

00:11:57.956 --> 00:12:00.366
>> I look at it from 2 lenses of

00:12:00.426 --> 00:12:00.666
care.

00:12:00.816 --> 00:12:02.056
Did I care enough to make it the

00:12:02.096 --> 00:12:02.706
best it could be?

00:12:02.706 --> 00:12:04.716
But do I also care about what

00:12:04.716 --> 00:12:05.816
your experience is?

00:12:06.436 --> 00:12:07.006
Be it you.

00:12:07.006 --> 00:12:08.196
Be it my mum.

00:12:08.196 --> 00:12:09.536
Be it my next-door neighbor.

00:12:09.536 --> 00:12:11.436
Be it anybody around the world.

00:12:11.796 --> 00:12:12.836
You have to kind of, sort of

00:12:12.936 --> 00:12:13.946
take yourself out of the

00:12:13.946 --> 00:12:15.266
equation, put yourself in their

00:12:15.266 --> 00:12:17.206
shoes so you can be sure that

00:12:17.206 --> 00:12:18.516
their experience is a quality

00:12:18.516 --> 00:12:19.216
experience.

00:12:19.616 --> 00:12:20.956
So you have to care enough to do

00:12:20.956 --> 00:12:21.246
that.

00:12:21.526 --> 00:12:22.776
It's not just about caring about

00:12:22.776 --> 00:12:25.026
your own sense of, "Oh, I like

00:12:25.116 --> 00:12:27.336
my design, and I cared enough to

00:12:27.336 --> 00:12:28.726
make it good for me."

00:12:28.916 --> 00:12:30.946
It's about it being good for as

00:12:30.946 --> 00:12:33.056
many people as possible or for

00:12:33.136 --> 00:12:34.326
the target audience, if it

00:12:34.326 --> 00:12:35.526
happens to be a more narrowly

00:12:35.526 --> 00:12:36.176
focused thing.

00:12:38.346 --> 00:12:40.326
>> Right. So when I heard this,

00:12:40.326 --> 00:12:41.836
I was just, I wanted to know

00:12:41.966 --> 00:12:43.426
how, immediately.

00:12:43.676 --> 00:12:45.276
How do you design that

00:12:45.276 --> 00:12:47.156
experience for others, and how

00:12:47.156 --> 00:12:48.076
do you know when you've made

00:12:48.116 --> 00:12:48.496
progress?

00:12:49.156 --> 00:12:51.846
>> I think sometimes we look at

00:12:51.846 --> 00:12:53.256
a tangled mess of problems that

00:12:53.256 --> 00:12:55.466
we need to solve, and if, at the

00:12:55.466 --> 00:12:57.006
end, you can look at the result

00:12:57.006 --> 00:12:58.906
and go, that is so much better,

00:12:58.906 --> 00:13:01.196
and if it came easy, it wouldn't

00:13:01.196 --> 00:13:02.786
be as fun, but the fact that you

00:13:02.786 --> 00:13:05.126
sweated over it, that you really

00:13:05.126 --> 00:13:06.216
worked hard at it, that it gave

00:13:06.216 --> 00:13:07.636
you sleepless nights, that you

00:13:08.606 --> 00:13:10.726
poured late nights and weekends

00:13:10.726 --> 00:13:12.346
into solving those problems,

00:13:12.346 --> 00:13:13.766
combined effort, team effort,

00:13:14.566 --> 00:13:16.606
the end result is so much more

00:13:16.606 --> 00:13:17.266
satisfying.

00:13:18.096 --> 00:13:19.826
I love it when we work hard and

00:13:20.296 --> 00:13:22.906
get there more than when ideas

00:13:22.906 --> 00:13:24.286
just come easily.

00:13:24.806 --> 00:13:25.816
I worry that we've actually

00:13:25.816 --> 00:13:27.136
missed something by not working

00:13:27.136 --> 00:13:27.436
hard.

00:13:27.496 --> 00:13:29.416
If it's too easy, we've become

00:13:29.416 --> 00:13:31.076
complacent, and I don't think

00:13:31.076 --> 00:13:32.866
you get anywhere rewarding

00:13:32.866 --> 00:13:36.256
without doing hard work.

00:13:36.456 --> 00:13:37.466
>> I really understood this

00:13:37.536 --> 00:13:40.396
point about working hard after

00:13:40.396 --> 00:13:42.806
Gary related this to mountain

00:13:42.806 --> 00:13:43.226
biking.

00:13:44.296 --> 00:13:45.176
We talked about this for a

00:13:45.176 --> 00:13:46.766
while, so I'm just going to

00:13:46.766 --> 00:13:48.126
summarize that conversation here

00:13:48.126 --> 00:13:48.766
for you today.

00:13:49.556 --> 00:13:51.186
Essentially, you have to work

00:13:51.346 --> 00:13:53.456
really hard to get to the top of

00:13:53.456 --> 00:13:55.316
the mountain, and then you can

00:13:55.316 --> 00:13:56.896
have a ton of fun on the

00:13:56.896 --> 00:13:57.286
descent.

00:13:57.986 --> 00:13:59.666
Now, it's not as much fun if you

00:13:59.666 --> 00:14:01.626
just started at the top and went

00:14:01.626 --> 00:14:04.276
down because it's really all of

00:14:04.276 --> 00:14:06.996
that time, and effort, and sweat

00:14:07.096 --> 00:14:08.186
that brings you to the top of

00:14:08.186 --> 00:14:10.486
the mountain that makes the view

00:14:10.486 --> 00:14:12.176
all that more beautiful and

00:14:12.176 --> 00:14:14.326
makes the ride down so much more

00:14:16.016 --> 00:14:16.136
fun.

00:14:16.366 --> 00:14:21.466
So in life, care naturally gives

00:14:21.466 --> 00:14:24.216
more time and effort because you

00:14:24.216 --> 00:14:25.926
have a passion to achieve your

00:14:25.926 --> 00:14:27.896
goals, and you'll do whatever is

00:14:27.956 --> 00:14:29.066
needed to meet your own

00:14:29.066 --> 00:14:29.976
expectations.

00:14:30.766 --> 00:14:32.626
And yeah, that's totally a lot

00:14:32.626 --> 00:14:35.216
of work, but that hard work has

00:14:35.216 --> 00:14:37.176
a payoff, and it's really

00:14:37.246 --> 00:14:37.986
satisfying.

00:14:38.736 --> 00:14:40.326
And the payoff, well, that's why

00:14:40.326 --> 00:14:41.566
you did it in the first place,

00:14:41.566 --> 00:14:41.816
right?

00:14:42.726 --> 00:14:44.766
You have a goal, and you make it

00:14:45.026 --> 00:14:45.226
happen.

00:14:45.976 --> 00:14:46.876
That's just awesome.

00:14:47.446 --> 00:14:51.076
So quality is all about care,

00:14:51.856 --> 00:14:53.456
and because you care, you're

00:14:53.456 --> 00:14:55.316
going to put in that time and

00:14:55.436 --> 00:14:56.846
effort to make things great.

00:14:57.306 --> 00:15:00.706
And that's just one answer to

00:15:00.706 --> 00:15:02.766
the question, what is quality?

00:15:03.906 --> 00:15:05.386
And because there are so many

00:15:05.386 --> 00:15:06.526
different interpretations of

00:15:06.526 --> 00:15:09.596
quality, well, that means it's

00:15:09.596 --> 00:15:11.396
just really hard to achieve.

00:15:12.336 --> 00:15:13.466
A little bit later, we're going

00:15:13.466 --> 00:15:15.186
to get into some techniques to

00:15:15.186 --> 00:15:16.726
hopefully help make the process

00:15:16.726 --> 00:15:17.626
of designing a little bit

00:15:17.656 --> 00:15:18.206
easier.

00:15:18.746 --> 00:15:20.396
But for now, let's just recap

00:15:20.536 --> 00:15:21.196
what we've learned.

00:15:21.786 --> 00:15:24.966
So far, just by asking a few

00:15:25.056 --> 00:15:27.056
simple questions, we've learned

00:15:27.186 --> 00:15:29.536
that quality means something

00:15:29.536 --> 00:15:30.766
different to different people,

00:15:32.206 --> 00:15:34.896
that it's not random -- it is

00:15:34.896 --> 00:15:36.486
crafted and considered.

00:15:37.636 --> 00:15:40.196
Quality is the result of time,

00:15:40.396 --> 00:15:41.546
effort, and care.

00:15:41.546 --> 00:15:45.836
And it is just hard to achieve,

00:15:46.596 --> 00:15:48.916
but that's okay.

00:15:49.156 --> 00:15:50.556
Quality has many different

00:15:50.556 --> 00:15:51.476
interpretations.

00:15:52.536 --> 00:15:53.236
What is yours?

00:15:53.236 --> 00:15:56.036
I think this is really important

00:15:56.036 --> 00:15:58.106
to ask yourself, what is

00:15:58.146 --> 00:15:59.356
quality, and what does it mean

00:15:59.356 --> 00:16:01.236
to you, and what does it mean to

00:16:01.236 --> 00:16:03.436
your app or game, because that's

00:16:03.436 --> 00:16:05.206
going to reveal what you truly

00:16:05.206 --> 00:16:06.716
care about, and that's going to

00:16:06.716 --> 00:16:08.066
help you focus on what you're

00:16:08.066 --> 00:16:09.566
working towards going forward.

00:16:10.106 --> 00:16:13.736
So let's just pause here for a

00:16:13.736 --> 00:16:15.106
moment, and we actually need to

00:16:15.106 --> 00:16:16.596
go back a bit.

00:16:16.596 --> 00:16:17.716
Why does quality matter in the

00:16:17.716 --> 00:16:18.356
first place?

00:16:18.436 --> 00:16:20.096
Why are we even talking about it

00:16:20.236 --> 00:16:21.706
here at WWDC?

00:16:21.786 --> 00:16:24.936
Well, what's the significance?

00:16:25.496 --> 00:16:28.346
Let's just ask, why is quality

00:16:28.646 --> 00:16:29.196
important?

00:16:30.536 --> 00:16:34.086
>> Quality impacts the world

00:16:34.086 --> 00:16:36.086
that we interact with in so many

00:16:36.086 --> 00:16:37.326
different ways all the time

00:16:37.416 --> 00:16:38.736
throughout our day.

00:16:39.816 --> 00:16:41.826
>> Yeah. Travis is totally

00:16:41.826 --> 00:16:41.986
right.

00:16:42.666 --> 00:16:43.826
Throughout our day, there are

00:16:43.916 --> 00:16:47.466
things that we eat, drink, wear,

00:16:47.466 --> 00:16:49.186
I mean, even the air we breathe.

00:16:49.286 --> 00:16:50.826
They all have some level of

00:16:50.826 --> 00:16:52.396
quality that impacts us.

00:16:53.326 --> 00:16:55.706
And we expect quality in our

00:16:55.816 --> 00:16:57.686
friendships, in our family, in

00:16:57.686 --> 00:16:58.616
our relationships.

00:16:59.296 --> 00:17:01.046
We seek out people who show us

00:17:01.046 --> 00:17:03.106
respect, who care about us and

00:17:03.106 --> 00:17:03.786
make us feel good.

00:17:03.786 --> 00:17:06.185
I mean, nobody keeps around

00:17:06.236 --> 00:17:07.286
poor-quality friends.

00:17:08.296 --> 00:17:09.786
We also expect quality from the

00:17:09.906 --> 00:17:11.516
products that we use and the

00:17:11.516 --> 00:17:12.986
things that we use every day.

00:17:13.715 --> 00:17:15.256
We expect them not to break.

00:17:16.205 --> 00:17:18.056
And if they do break, well, we

00:17:18.056 --> 00:17:19.286
tend to think that they're cheap

00:17:19.806 --> 00:17:22.026
and not well made, and we

00:17:22.106 --> 00:17:24.215
typically won't buy them again.

00:17:25.136 --> 00:17:27.906
So yeah, the concept of quality

00:17:28.706 --> 00:17:30.686
impacts our every day, and it's

00:17:30.746 --> 00:17:32.036
really in everything.

00:17:33.036 --> 00:17:34.826
While it's really wide reaching

00:17:34.826 --> 00:17:36.786
and broad, there seems to be

00:17:36.786 --> 00:17:39.226
something so special about

00:17:39.226 --> 00:17:41.156
quality, but what is it?

00:17:41.606 --> 00:17:43.176
What makes quality special?

00:17:44.696 --> 00:17:46.116
>> They say, like, oh, I cooked

00:17:46.566 --> 00:17:47.816
this with love, and it can just

00:17:47.856 --> 00:17:49.966
be eggs or whatever, but it does

00:17:50.096 --> 00:17:52.196
taste different, and I think

00:17:52.196 --> 00:17:53.326
Jessie and I like to think that

00:17:54.106 --> 00:17:56.256
whatever we do, that sort of

00:17:56.256 --> 00:17:57.686
love for what we're doing comes

00:17:57.756 --> 00:17:58.516
through.

00:17:59.006 --> 00:18:01.136
>> Right? I know these two

00:18:01.136 --> 00:18:02.946
ladies absolutely love what they

00:18:02.946 --> 00:18:05.556
do, and I know I can feel it

00:18:05.556 --> 00:18:07.046
when someone really loves

00:18:07.046 --> 00:18:07.676
something.

00:18:08.436 --> 00:18:10.356
And to Elaine's first point, you

00:18:10.356 --> 00:18:11.376
know, I think everyone here

00:18:11.376 --> 00:18:13.566
knows that Mom and Dad's food

00:18:13.566 --> 00:18:15.266
just tastes a little bit better

00:18:15.666 --> 00:18:17.696
because it's made with that care

00:18:17.836 --> 00:18:18.336
and love.

00:18:19.576 --> 00:18:21.726
So what really Elaine means by

00:18:21.726 --> 00:18:24.416
this is your intentions are

00:18:24.416 --> 00:18:24.706
felt.

00:18:25.856 --> 00:18:27.296
So if your intention is to

00:18:27.296 --> 00:18:29.416
create something great and you

00:18:29.416 --> 00:18:31.086
do everything you need to do to

00:18:31.086 --> 00:18:32.716
achieve that, people are going

00:18:32.716 --> 00:18:33.216
to know.

00:18:33.536 --> 00:18:35.586
They're going to feel it.

00:18:35.586 --> 00:18:36.856
And the reverse is true too.

00:18:37.306 --> 00:18:38.916
You know, if you rushed and you

00:18:38.916 --> 00:18:40.206
didn't really care about the

00:18:40.206 --> 00:18:41.656
look of settings in your app UI,

00:18:42.456 --> 00:18:44.476
well, it's going to impact the

00:18:44.476 --> 00:18:46.946
overall feeling that people have

00:18:47.106 --> 00:18:48.406
about your app.

00:18:50.436 --> 00:18:52.016
So throughout the course of

00:18:52.016 --> 00:18:53.906
conducting these interviews, I

00:18:53.906 --> 00:18:54.986
started to see the word

00:18:55.026 --> 00:18:57.236
"quality" everywhere, like

00:18:57.726 --> 00:19:00.426
quality coffee or quality meats.

00:19:01.516 --> 00:19:02.826
And even one night when I was

00:19:02.876 --> 00:19:03.936
working really late, and I

00:19:03.936 --> 00:19:05.366
ordered a pizza, and the pizza

00:19:05.366 --> 00:19:07.566
box said, "Our commitment is

00:19:07.566 --> 00:19:08.286
quality."

00:19:09.076 --> 00:19:11.106
[laughs] So I see the word

00:19:11.106 --> 00:19:12.346
everywhere now.

00:19:12.446 --> 00:19:14.516
It's really pervasive, from

00:19:14.636 --> 00:19:16.746
signs to badges, to labels.

00:19:17.366 --> 00:19:19.246
So I brought this up in a few of

00:19:19.246 --> 00:19:21.106
the interviews, not because I

00:19:21.106 --> 00:19:22.236
wanted to know what people

00:19:22.236 --> 00:19:23.866
thought of labeling, but,

00:19:23.866 --> 00:19:26.886
instead, to ask, why do we tend

00:19:26.886 --> 00:19:28.866
to be drawn towards things that

00:19:28.866 --> 00:19:29.606
are quality?

00:19:31.516 --> 00:19:34.066
>> Well, survival instinct at

00:19:34.066 --> 00:19:34.556
its root.

00:19:35.036 --> 00:19:36.536
On a more deep level, I guess,

00:19:36.536 --> 00:19:37.806
why do we desire quality?

00:19:38.296 --> 00:19:39.826
We desire quality because we

00:19:39.826 --> 00:19:40.406
want to live.

00:19:41.176 --> 00:19:44.096
And a good survival strategy for

00:19:44.096 --> 00:19:47.626
living is to put things into our

00:19:47.626 --> 00:19:50.296
body, to eat things, or to wear

00:19:50.296 --> 00:19:52.066
things, or to drive in things,

00:19:52.066 --> 00:19:54.396
or to live in things that are

00:19:54.656 --> 00:19:56.936
safe and have been well

00:19:56.936 --> 00:19:59.036
constructed so they aren't going

00:19:59.036 --> 00:20:00.936
to cause us bodily harm.

00:20:01.616 --> 00:20:04.906
And so I think purely on a

00:20:04.906 --> 00:20:07.236
survival level, quality is a

00:20:07.236 --> 00:20:08.986
very important concept for us.

00:20:08.986 --> 00:20:10.376
It's a very important attribute

00:20:10.376 --> 00:20:11.666
that we seek in everything.

00:20:14.256 --> 00:20:16.356
>> Mike explained a bit further

00:20:16.356 --> 00:20:17.336
during this interview.

00:20:17.746 --> 00:20:18.996
We were talking about this

00:20:19.196 --> 00:20:22.356
fictitious butcher shop, and if

00:20:22.356 --> 00:20:24.296
we were in this shop, quality

00:20:24.296 --> 00:20:25.886
would be communicated not only

00:20:25.886 --> 00:20:28.266
by the products itself, but also

00:20:28.266 --> 00:20:30.706
the shop being really clean and

00:20:30.706 --> 00:20:31.946
interacting with the really nice

00:20:32.076 --> 00:20:33.146
people that work there.

00:20:34.236 --> 00:20:36.246
Every facet of the entire

00:20:36.246 --> 00:20:38.776
experience would meet your

00:20:38.776 --> 00:20:40.436
expectations, [laughs] and it

00:20:40.436 --> 00:20:42.506
would also be connected to that

00:20:42.646 --> 00:20:44.216
proposition of quality.

00:20:44.796 --> 00:20:48.266
And that evokes trust.

00:20:49.546 --> 00:20:51.296
Trust comes from products

00:20:51.366 --> 00:20:53.906
upholding their promise, and

00:20:53.906 --> 00:20:56.046
that quality experience is far

00:20:56.046 --> 00:20:57.956
more important than any label

00:20:58.416 --> 00:21:00.046
because I am definitely not

00:21:00.256 --> 00:21:02.986
suggesting that you add a label

00:21:02.986 --> 00:21:04.996
to your apps because you

00:21:04.996 --> 00:21:06.266
[laughs] definitely don't need

00:21:06.886 --> 00:21:07.426
to.

