Every facet of your app

00:21:10.186 --> 00:21:12.496
experience, from the screenshots

00:21:12.496 --> 00:21:14.006
on the App Store to the

00:21:14.006 --> 00:21:16.596
description, to how you respond

00:21:16.596 --> 00:21:19.196
to customer reviews, all through

00:21:19.196 --> 00:21:21.716
to your app's interface, these

00:21:21.716 --> 00:21:23.396
experiences, these interactions

00:21:23.396 --> 00:21:25.296
that you have with people, that

00:21:25.296 --> 00:21:27.566
communicates the quality about

00:21:27.566 --> 00:21:28.996
your app or your game.

00:21:29.936 --> 00:21:31.556
And you don't want a label

00:21:31.556 --> 00:21:32.166
anyway.

00:21:32.946 --> 00:21:33.316
Why?

00:21:35.266 --> 00:21:37.436
>> In a way, it's like saying

00:21:37.436 --> 00:21:38.226
you're cool.

00:21:38.656 --> 00:21:41.476
Like, being cool doesn't involve

00:21:41.806 --> 00:21:42.786
saying you're cool.

00:21:43.326 --> 00:21:46.396
[laughs] And, you know, you only

00:21:46.476 --> 00:21:48.096
say that someone else is cool.

00:21:48.096 --> 00:21:49.986
It's only something which can be

00:21:49.986 --> 00:21:51.626
sort of determined by an outside

00:21:51.626 --> 00:21:52.486
party, in a way.

00:21:53.656 --> 00:21:56.146
And even then, there's a certain

00:21:56.146 --> 00:21:57.196
context where it feels more

00:21:57.196 --> 00:21:58.316
appropriate than others.

00:21:58.316 --> 00:21:59.396
Like, if we're talking about

00:21:59.816 --> 00:22:01.976
Thelonious Monk and we're just

00:22:01.976 --> 00:22:03.576
talking about jazz in the '50's,

00:22:03.676 --> 00:22:04.806
like, that's cool.

00:22:05.066 --> 00:22:06.546
That's the birth of cool, right.

00:22:06.546 --> 00:22:08.476
[laughs] That's where it's,

00:22:08.476 --> 00:22:10.296
like, totally appropriate to use

00:22:10.296 --> 00:22:13.586
that kind of term, but that's an

00:22:13.586 --> 00:22:14.776
earned coolness.

00:22:15.066 --> 00:22:17.146
And so quality has to be earned.

00:22:17.756 --> 00:22:19.926
>> I think Mike makes a really

00:22:19.926 --> 00:22:20.386
good point.

00:22:20.916 --> 00:22:24.126
So the significance of quality

00:22:24.126 --> 00:22:24.916
is massive.

00:22:25.086 --> 00:22:27.416
As we heard, it impacts our

00:22:27.466 --> 00:22:30.356
every day, it can be felt, and

00:22:30.416 --> 00:22:32.306
it evokes trust in the people

00:22:32.306 --> 00:22:33.906
that are using your app.

00:22:35.196 --> 00:22:35.686
All right.

00:22:37.106 --> 00:22:39.046
Now, everyone I talked to

00:22:39.106 --> 00:22:39.996
throughout these interviews,

00:22:40.076 --> 00:22:42.066
they all have a passion for

00:22:42.066 --> 00:22:43.986
excellence, so we're going to

00:22:43.986 --> 00:22:45.606
talk about four design

00:22:45.866 --> 00:22:47.706
aspirations, and these four

00:22:47.706 --> 00:22:49.366
aspirations really stood out to

00:22:49.366 --> 00:22:51.116
me because, well, they seemed

00:22:51.116 --> 00:22:53.306
just so incredibly elusive and

00:22:53.306 --> 00:22:54.186
hard to achieve.

00:22:54.686 --> 00:22:57.776
But these designers use them as

00:22:57.776 --> 00:23:00.046
motivation to strive for quality

00:23:00.046 --> 00:23:01.866
in their work, and these

00:23:01.866 --> 00:23:04.116
aspirations are to design things

00:23:04.376 --> 00:23:07.846
that are simple, stunning,

00:23:09.436 --> 00:23:12.746
timeless, and leave a positive

00:23:12.746 --> 00:23:13.916
impact on people's lives.

00:23:14.996 --> 00:23:16.326
So we're going to dig into each

00:23:16.366 --> 00:23:18.246
one of these to discover why

00:23:18.246 --> 00:23:20.536
they're important and also how

00:23:20.536 --> 00:23:22.066
they provide motivation to

00:23:22.066 --> 00:23:23.236
create great design.

00:23:24.916 --> 00:23:25.246
All right.

00:23:25.876 --> 00:23:27.586
Let's start with simplicity.

00:23:27.846 --> 00:23:30.846
This came up in response to this

00:23:30.896 --> 00:23:33.306
question: What makes a great

00:23:33.376 --> 00:23:33.576
app?

00:23:35.446 --> 00:23:36.206
>> It's simple.

00:23:36.596 --> 00:23:38.566
It doesn't try to do more than

00:23:38.566 --> 00:23:39.466
it needs to do.

00:23:39.866 --> 00:23:40.996
And what it does, it does it

00:23:41.066 --> 00:23:41.676
really well.

00:23:41.676 --> 00:23:44.226
>> I don't know about you, but I

00:23:44.226 --> 00:23:45.696
have heard that a lot.

00:23:46.546 --> 00:23:47.896
[laughs] So I'm sure you've

00:23:47.896 --> 00:23:48.846
heard it before too.

00:23:49.346 --> 00:23:51.246
But there's got to be a reason

00:23:51.246 --> 00:23:53.206
why that phrase is on repeat,

00:23:53.926 --> 00:23:56.036
and I was really thinking about

00:23:56.036 --> 00:23:57.166
this after the interview.

00:23:57.166 --> 00:23:59.686
You know, why should apps be

00:23:59.686 --> 00:24:01.106
simple, and why is that a good

00:24:01.106 --> 00:24:01.476
thing?

00:24:02.276 --> 00:24:03.926
Well, it finally clicked for me

00:24:03.926 --> 00:24:05.176
one day after work.

00:24:06.326 --> 00:24:08.006
I got home, I needed to cook

00:24:08.006 --> 00:24:09.736
some dinner, and I needed an app

00:24:10.026 --> 00:24:11.856
to help me with a recipe, to not

00:24:11.856 --> 00:24:13.306
make cooking any harder than it

00:24:13.306 --> 00:24:13.966
already is.

00:24:14.566 --> 00:24:15.806
And as soon as I was home, I

00:24:16.066 --> 00:24:18.156
remembered that I needed to go

00:24:18.156 --> 00:24:20.166
ahead and put, book pet care for

00:24:20.166 --> 00:24:21.936
my two dogs because I'm going on

00:24:21.936 --> 00:24:22.846
vacation after WWDC.

00:24:22.846 --> 00:24:23.786
Aw, aren't they cute?

00:24:24.736 --> 00:24:28.176
[laughs] Okay, we have to stop

00:24:28.176 --> 00:24:29.066
before I get distracted.

00:24:29.066 --> 00:24:31.136
We're talking about two tasks

00:24:31.476 --> 00:24:34.176
here, cooking dinner and pet

00:24:34.246 --> 00:24:34.476
care.

00:24:35.636 --> 00:24:36.906
Why do the apps that help me

00:24:36.906 --> 00:24:38.166
with those, why do they need to

00:24:38.166 --> 00:24:38.826
be simple?

00:24:38.876 --> 00:24:41.546
Well, it's because I don't go

00:24:41.546 --> 00:24:43.746
into them all the time, so they

00:24:43.746 --> 00:24:44.886
need to be instantly

00:24:44.886 --> 00:24:46.546
understandable, as if I already

00:24:46.546 --> 00:24:47.526
know how to use them.

00:24:47.996 --> 00:24:49.556
So familiar navigation and

00:24:49.556 --> 00:24:50.616
gestures really help with that.

00:24:51.616 --> 00:24:53.196
You know, the goal is launch the

00:24:53.196 --> 00:24:55.536
app, I totally get it, and I can

00:24:55.536 --> 00:24:56.466
get the task done.

00:24:57.466 --> 00:24:58.766
But why else should they be

00:24:58.766 --> 00:24:59.206
simple?

00:25:00.286 --> 00:25:02.696
Well, it could be a good day or

00:25:02.696 --> 00:25:04.626
a bad day, but I'm using these

00:25:04.626 --> 00:25:07.266
apps in real life, and that's

00:25:07.266 --> 00:25:08.526
where all of my mental energy

00:25:08.526 --> 00:25:10.666
should be, not wasted on a

00:25:10.666 --> 00:25:13.066
confusing app UI, interaction,

00:25:13.296 --> 00:25:14.086
or interface.

00:25:14.756 --> 00:25:17.116
Apps should not be a burden, and

00:25:17.116 --> 00:25:18.696
it's a lot easier to get back to

00:25:18.696 --> 00:25:20.126
real life when they're simple.

00:25:21.086 --> 00:25:22.986
So how would you describe

00:25:23.046 --> 00:25:25.016
simplicity in apps and games?

00:25:25.096 --> 00:25:27.986
>> It just has to work.

00:25:28.086 --> 00:25:31.056
>> Right. It just has to work

00:25:31.056 --> 00:25:32.346
for the people that are using

00:25:32.346 --> 00:25:32.636
it.

00:25:32.916 --> 00:25:34.056
But there's actually something

00:25:34.056 --> 00:25:34.636
else here.

00:25:35.636 --> 00:25:36.876
You don't want people to feel

00:25:36.876 --> 00:25:37.806
distracted.

00:25:38.346 --> 00:25:40.756
Simple, easy-to-understand apps

00:25:41.086 --> 00:25:43.096
that just work, well, they help

00:25:43.136 --> 00:25:44.276
keep people focused.

00:25:45.236 --> 00:25:46.566
I know for me, I can get really

00:25:46.566 --> 00:25:47.776
easily overwhelmed if

00:25:47.846 --> 00:25:49.236
something's out of place.

00:25:49.276 --> 00:25:50.446
It can just take me out of that

00:25:50.446 --> 00:25:52.246
experience, and that makes

00:25:52.316 --> 00:25:53.956
getting the task done even

00:25:53.956 --> 00:25:54.426
harder.

00:25:54.426 --> 00:25:56.466
I was actually talking to Jessie

00:25:56.466 --> 00:25:58.706
about this, and I asked her,

00:25:59.126 --> 00:26:00.806
what does she look for in great

00:26:01.006 --> 00:26:01.326
apps?

00:26:01.866 --> 00:26:04.246
>> Make my life feel a little

00:26:04.246 --> 00:26:06.396
bit easier or make my life feel

00:26:06.396 --> 00:26:08.026
a little bit nicer or more

00:26:08.026 --> 00:26:08.816
luxurious.

00:26:09.616 --> 00:26:11.566
>> I think that is just spot on.

00:26:12.236 --> 00:26:13.946
Make my life feel a little bit

00:26:13.946 --> 00:26:17.166
easier by being simple, focused,

00:26:18.096 --> 00:26:20.086
instantly understandable, and

00:26:20.086 --> 00:26:22.936
just do one thing really, really

00:26:22.936 --> 00:26:23.076
well.

00:26:23.996 --> 00:26:24.926
That is the goal.

00:26:25.396 --> 00:26:29.206
All right, this next aspiration

00:26:29.206 --> 00:26:31.676
is to be stunning, and this came

00:26:31.676 --> 00:26:32.716
up when I was talking to

00:26:32.836 --> 00:26:33.406
Caroline.

00:26:33.816 --> 00:26:36.626
I asked her, "What communicates

00:26:36.936 --> 00:26:38.466
great visual design?"

00:26:39.166 --> 00:26:41.786
>> Just that polish.

00:26:42.206 --> 00:26:43.646
Does it look great?

00:26:43.646 --> 00:26:44.866
Does it look stunning?

00:26:45.406 --> 00:26:46.826
And then, the other level of

00:26:46.826 --> 00:26:48.926
polish, on a different kind of

00:26:48.926 --> 00:26:50.516
app, like a game or something,

00:26:50.516 --> 00:26:52.716
to me is making it feel

00:26:52.836 --> 00:26:54.806
beautiful as an experience, like

00:26:54.806 --> 00:26:56.296
it feels like a work of art.

00:26:57.626 --> 00:26:58.666
>> Right, yes.

00:26:59.436 --> 00:27:00.476
So we talked a little bit

00:27:00.476 --> 00:27:02.536
further about this, and Caroline

00:27:02.536 --> 00:27:04.656
explained that what she means by

00:27:04.806 --> 00:27:07.636
polish is things lining up just

00:27:07.716 --> 00:27:08.986
the way you intend them to be,

00:27:09.506 --> 00:27:10.956
including how it feels.

00:27:10.956 --> 00:27:12.346
You know, swipe animations

00:27:12.626 --> 00:27:14.006
lining right up with those swipe

00:27:14.046 --> 00:27:14.596
gestures.

00:27:15.416 --> 00:27:17.036
And the best apps appear

00:27:17.036 --> 00:27:18.916
visually perfect, and that is

00:27:18.976 --> 00:27:20.346
just totally remarkable.

00:27:20.896 --> 00:27:22.506
And she also mentioned games.

00:27:23.216 --> 00:27:25.676
Games should absolutely aspire

00:27:25.776 --> 00:27:26.406
to be stunning.

00:27:27.226 --> 00:27:29.706
Games are a perfect escape from

00:27:29.706 --> 00:27:32.316
this world into a different one.

00:27:32.896 --> 00:27:34.656
And they accomplish this through

00:27:34.656 --> 00:27:36.586
stunning, immersive visuals.

00:27:37.806 --> 00:27:39.466
I mean, I love TV and movies,

00:27:39.546 --> 00:27:41.056
but that's a really passive

00:27:41.056 --> 00:27:41.626
escape.

00:27:42.186 --> 00:27:43.416
In games, well, they're an

00:27:43.416 --> 00:27:44.986
active one, and that's why I

00:27:45.046 --> 00:27:45.586
love them.

00:27:46.396 --> 00:27:48.036
But there is one essential thing

00:27:48.386 --> 00:27:49.896
that all games must do.

00:27:50.966 --> 00:27:53.386
They must teach you, the player,

00:27:53.626 --> 00:27:53.926
the rules.

00:27:53.926 --> 00:27:56.086
And this is really a first

00:27:56.086 --> 00:27:57.536
impression that people have of a

00:27:57.536 --> 00:27:59.996
lot of games, so it makes me

00:27:59.996 --> 00:28:02.426
really sad when games make a bad

00:28:02.486 --> 00:28:04.746
first impression because when

00:28:04.746 --> 00:28:06.946
I'm trying to learn, well, the

00:28:06.946 --> 00:28:08.576
rules feel slapped together,

00:28:09.066 --> 00:28:11.076
added on last minute, or it just

00:28:11.076 --> 00:28:12.316
doesn't feel a part of the

00:28:12.316 --> 00:28:13.086
game's world.

00:28:13.086 --> 00:28:16.706
So I decided to ask Sam, who's

00:28:16.706 --> 00:28:18.136
working on an upcoming game

00:28:18.136 --> 00:28:20.416
called Where Cards Fall, "How do

00:28:20.416 --> 00:28:22.036
you learn the rules of the game

00:28:22.346 --> 00:28:24.116
all while staying in the game's

00:28:24.116 --> 00:28:24.436
world?"

00:28:24.926 --> 00:28:27.326
>> With games in particular,

00:28:27.326 --> 00:28:29.066
there's a real joy that can come

00:28:29.166 --> 00:28:31.196
from discovering what they can

00:28:31.196 --> 00:28:33.126
do and learning for yourself.

00:28:33.186 --> 00:28:34.916
People tend to remember things

00:28:35.046 --> 00:28:37.206
the best when they experience

00:28:37.206 --> 00:28:38.636
them themselves, when they learn

00:28:38.826 --> 00:28:40.496
them through some sort of active

00:28:40.496 --> 00:28:41.526
discovery.

00:28:41.526 --> 00:28:43.996
So if we give them too much at

00:28:43.996 --> 00:28:45.556
the beginning, we're robbing

00:28:45.556 --> 00:28:47.296
them of that chance to reward

00:28:47.296 --> 00:28:48.386
their own curiosity.

00:28:48.696 --> 00:28:49.926
So we always want to make sure

00:28:49.986 --> 00:28:51.446
that they stay curious, that

00:28:51.446 --> 00:28:52.586
they stay interested throughout

00:28:52.586 --> 00:28:54.976
the entire experience, and that

00:28:55.076 --> 00:28:56.046
they have a lot of different

00:28:56.046 --> 00:28:57.176
moments where they can be

00:28:57.176 --> 00:28:58.566
rewarded for trying something.

00:28:58.566 --> 00:29:00.086
And when they try something and

00:29:00.086 --> 00:29:01.546
they discover something for the

00:29:01.546 --> 00:29:03.126
first time, they definitely

00:29:03.126 --> 00:29:03.806
won't forget it.

00:29:03.806 --> 00:29:04.886
But if we throw up like a

00:29:04.886 --> 00:29:06.746
tooltip or some way of just

00:29:06.746 --> 00:29:08.676
making sure that we as the game

00:29:08.676 --> 00:29:09.746
designers are comfortable

00:29:09.746 --> 00:29:10.426
knowing that they know

00:29:10.426 --> 00:29:12.206
something, there's a pretty good

00:29:12.206 --> 00:29:13.066
chance that they'll forget it

00:29:13.066 --> 00:29:14.676
later on since they didn't go

00:29:14.676 --> 00:29:15.676
through the process of learning

00:29:15.676 --> 00:29:15.976
it themselves.

00:29:19.976 --> 00:29:21.826
So when I go into a game for the

00:29:21.916 --> 00:29:24.476
first time, I want to learn how

00:29:24.476 --> 00:29:26.776
to navigate the world, if it

00:29:26.776 --> 00:29:29.296
takes place in a world, as

00:29:29.296 --> 00:29:30.496
quickly as possible or just how

00:29:30.496 --> 00:29:31.656
to understand the rules of the

00:29:31.656 --> 00:29:33.956
game as quickly as possible, but

00:29:34.146 --> 00:29:35.986
not so quickly that I'm kind of

00:29:35.986 --> 00:29:37.266
robbed of my curiosity to

00:29:37.266 --> 00:29:38.446
explore them a little bit

00:29:38.526 --> 00:29:38.896
further.

00:29:39.446 --> 00:29:42.546
So I tend to get a sense for

00:29:42.626 --> 00:29:44.646
what the game is, and if the

00:29:44.646 --> 00:29:46.466
game continues to surprise me,

00:29:46.796 --> 00:29:48.716
I'll make it through to the

00:29:48.716 --> 00:29:50.016
finish line.

00:29:51.286 --> 00:29:53.376
>> Wow, that was learning the

00:29:53.376 --> 00:29:55.436
rules in Where Cards Fall, and

00:29:55.576 --> 00:29:57.156
that definitely feels a part of

00:29:57.156 --> 00:29:59.626
the game's world, and I think

00:29:59.626 --> 00:30:01.136
everyone can learn from what Sam

00:30:01.176 --> 00:30:03.266
said about active discovery.

00:30:03.706 --> 00:30:05.256
And this is not just for games.

00:30:05.766 --> 00:30:07.696
Active discovery is so much

00:30:07.736 --> 00:30:09.696
better than reading tooltips or

00:30:09.696 --> 00:30:12.106
chasing a pointing arrow, and to

00:30:12.196 --> 00:30:14.826
Sam's point, being told isn't as

00:30:14.826 --> 00:30:17.206
much fun or, frankly, effective

00:30:17.436 --> 00:30:19.016
as discovering something for

00:30:19.016 --> 00:30:19.516
yourself.

00:30:20.686 --> 00:30:22.346
It's kind of like being told

00:30:22.346 --> 00:30:24.876
about a vacation versus being on

00:30:24.876 --> 00:30:25.906
that vacation yourself.

00:30:26.706 --> 00:30:28.246
It's way more fun, and you're

00:30:28.246 --> 00:30:29.666
just going to remember it better

00:30:29.666 --> 00:30:31.416
if you actually go through that

00:30:31.416 --> 00:30:32.116
experience.

00:30:33.536 --> 00:30:35.106
So whether you're creating an

00:30:35.106 --> 00:30:38.176
app or a game, aspire to be

00:30:38.176 --> 00:30:38.776
stunning.

00:30:39.216 --> 00:30:41.136
Create beautiful experiences,

00:30:41.646 --> 00:30:43.696
polish your visual design so it

00:30:43.696 --> 00:30:45.856
looks and feels just a part of

00:30:45.856 --> 00:30:47.436
your app or game's world.

00:30:47.956 --> 00:30:49.816
Okay, timeless.

00:30:51.236 --> 00:30:54.156
This has been on my mind since

00:30:54.206 --> 00:30:55.586
talking with Hugo, a sound

00:30:55.586 --> 00:30:56.036
designer.

00:30:56.716 --> 00:30:59.136
Most of you will recognize this.

00:31:00.516 --> 00:31:10.196
[ Ringtone ]

00:31:10.696 --> 00:31:11.876
I'm always looking for where

00:31:11.876 --> 00:31:13.296
that phone is.

00:31:13.496 --> 00:31:14.926
But what reminded me of this

00:31:14.966 --> 00:31:17.726
ringtone was this part of the

00:31:17.726 --> 00:31:18.376
interview.

00:31:18.976 --> 00:31:23.406
>> If we create a ringtone for

00:31:24.076 --> 00:31:27.126
the new iPhone, then we don't

00:31:27.126 --> 00:31:28.916
want it to sound dated after a

00:31:28.916 --> 00:31:29.776
year, of course.

00:31:29.776 --> 00:31:31.766
It should still be a great

00:31:32.356 --> 00:31:34.606
ringtone after 5 years, and

00:31:34.606 --> 00:31:35.946
maybe people will still remember

00:31:35.946 --> 00:31:36.936
it after 10 years.

00:31:37.476 --> 00:31:41.286
>> It was actually this section

00:31:41.696 --> 00:31:43.456
of the quote that really made me

00:31:43.576 --> 00:31:45.116
think of timelessness.

00:31:46.316 --> 00:31:47.486
You know, it makes sense for a

00:31:47.486 --> 00:31:49.126
ringtone not to want to sound

00:31:49.126 --> 00:31:51.706
dated, but this could also apply

00:31:51.706 --> 00:31:53.246
to your visual and interaction

00:31:53.246 --> 00:31:54.256
design too.

00:31:55.376 --> 00:31:57.726
Hugo used this word "durability"

00:31:57.986 --> 00:32:00.006
to describe quality during our

00:32:00.006 --> 00:32:01.686
interview, and I think that's

00:32:01.846 --> 00:32:02.476
really great.

00:32:03.256 --> 00:32:04.996
If we all aspire to create

00:32:04.996 --> 00:32:06.246
designs that are just a little

00:32:06.246 --> 00:32:08.556
bit longer lasting, it not only

00:32:08.556 --> 00:32:10.036
would save us time and effort

00:32:10.036 --> 00:32:12.596
now, but it would put us into

00:32:12.596 --> 00:32:14.536
the right mindset to provide

00:32:14.586 --> 00:32:15.806
something that we create with

00:32:15.806 --> 00:32:20.916
the opportunity to be timeless.

00:32:21.036 --> 00:32:23.466
This final aspiration really had

00:32:23.466 --> 00:32:25.536
an impact on me, and it came

00:32:25.536 --> 00:32:27.166
from my colleague Doug when I

00:32:27.166 --> 00:32:29.376
asked him, "What makes great app

00:32:29.506 --> 00:32:29.976
experiences?"

00:32:32.216 --> 00:32:34.126
>> When I think of, like, great

00:32:34.246 --> 00:32:36.366
app experiences and things that

00:32:36.446 --> 00:32:38.466
kind of provide something unique

00:32:38.466 --> 00:32:40.676
and valuable to users, I think a

00:32:40.676 --> 00:32:43.556
lot of it is the substantial

00:32:43.556 --> 00:32:45.496
kind of positive effect that it

00:32:45.496 --> 00:32:47.546
has on the user's life.

00:32:48.996 --> 00:32:51.066
>> Doug, you nailed it.

00:32:51.526 --> 00:32:53.486
Yes, absolutely, apps should

00:32:53.486 --> 00:32:54.956
provide something unique and

00:32:54.956 --> 00:32:57.366
valuable, but, actually, it was

00:32:57.366 --> 00:32:58.946
this part, the positive effect,

00:32:59.216 --> 00:33:00.796
that really resonated with me.

00:33:01.806 --> 00:33:03.966
It made me reassess the apps and

00:33:03.966 --> 00:33:04.916
games on my phone.

00:33:05.476 --> 00:33:06.726
After this interview, I

00:33:06.726 --> 00:33:08.786
literally scrolled through all

00:33:08.786 --> 00:33:10.876
of my apps, and I thought, which

00:33:10.876 --> 00:33:13.136
ones have a positive effect on

00:33:13.226 --> 00:33:14.286
my life?

00:33:14.916 --> 00:33:17.036
You know, wouldn't it be great

00:33:17.546 --> 00:33:19.346
if life just had a little more

00:33:19.476 --> 00:33:20.226
positivity?

00:33:21.616 --> 00:33:24.396
So next time you design, strive

00:33:24.396 --> 00:33:26.676
for simplicity because real life

00:33:26.876 --> 00:33:28.086
if where we need to be spending

00:33:28.086 --> 00:33:28.736
our energy.

00:33:29.936 --> 00:33:32.826
Aspire to be stunning because we

00:33:32.826 --> 00:33:34.896
all need a break from chaos, and

00:33:34.896 --> 00:33:36.676
it's really nice to escape and

00:33:36.676 --> 00:33:38.056
experience something beautiful.

00:33:38.566 --> 00:33:41.016
Design to be timeless.

00:33:41.776 --> 00:33:43.126
Think about how your designs can

00:33:43.126 --> 00:33:45.586
be good now but also years from

00:33:45.586 --> 00:33:47.826
now because we could all design

00:33:47.866 --> 00:33:49.666
to be a little less trendy and

00:33:49.666 --> 00:33:51.006
definitely more durable.

00:33:51.606 --> 00:33:54.806
And finally, think about how you

00:33:54.806 --> 00:33:56.456
could have a positive impact on

00:33:56.456 --> 00:33:56.916
people's lives.

00:33:58.196 --> 00:33:59.456
And, you know, this can manifest

00:33:59.496 --> 00:34:01.216
itself in really different ways

00:34:01.216 --> 00:34:02.896
depending on your app.

00:34:02.896 --> 00:34:04.166
It could be maybe that

00:34:04.166 --> 00:34:05.586
positivity is being really

00:34:05.586 --> 00:34:07.566
accurate, or maybe it's just

00:34:07.566 --> 00:34:08.706
being super entertaining.

00:34:09.616 --> 00:34:10.806
Maybe it's just making someone's

00:34:10.806 --> 00:34:13.216
life or day feel a little bit

00:34:13.216 --> 00:34:13.656
easier.

00:34:13.656 --> 00:34:16.466
I hope that you found some of

00:34:16.466 --> 00:34:17.396
these thoughts to be as

00:34:17.396 --> 00:34:18.706
inspiring as I did.

00:34:20.255 --> 00:34:21.186
I'm sure you're thinking now,

00:34:21.186 --> 00:34:22.735
though, well, sure, this has

00:34:22.735 --> 00:34:24.545
been mildly inspiring and

00:34:24.636 --> 00:34:26.706
somewhat educational, but what

00:34:26.706 --> 00:34:27.585
can I do?

00:34:27.585 --> 00:34:29.196
What can I actually take away

00:34:29.196 --> 00:34:30.476
and apply to my work?

00:34:30.476 --> 00:34:33.186
Well, I wanted to know that too.

00:34:33.906 --> 00:34:35.326
After talking with so many

00:34:35.326 --> 00:34:36.536
different people from different

00:34:36.536 --> 00:34:38.545
backgrounds, I wanted to know

00:34:38.646 --> 00:34:40.426
what they learned -- what they

00:34:40.426 --> 00:34:42.045
learned on the job through their

00:34:42.045 --> 00:34:43.036
experiences.

00:34:43.576 --> 00:34:44.476
So through a series of

00:34:44.476 --> 00:34:46.456
questions, I uncovered a few

00:34:46.606 --> 00:34:48.616
tips and techniques that these

00:34:48.616 --> 00:34:50.755
designers use regularly when

00:34:50.755 --> 00:34:51.306
designing.

00:34:52.005 --> 00:34:53.295
And something important to

00:34:53.295 --> 00:34:54.786
mention about design before we

00:34:54.786 --> 00:34:58.726
get started is, yes, design is

00:34:58.756 --> 00:35:01.306
hard because nobody sets out to

00:35:01.306 --> 00:35:02.196
create a bad app.

00:35:02.966 --> 00:35:04.866
Making great designs is what we

00:35:04.946 --> 00:35:07.796
all strive for, but let's be

00:35:07.796 --> 00:35:08.206
honest.

00:35:08.816 --> 00:35:11.136
We don't always achieve it, and

00:35:11.136 --> 00:35:12.956
that's okay because we keep

00:35:12.956 --> 00:35:15.296
trying and we learn a lot along

00:35:15.296 --> 00:35:15.516
the way.

00:35:16.796 --> 00:35:19.756
Okay, let's go ahead and hear

00:35:19.756 --> 00:35:21.546
this first technique, and it

00:35:21.546 --> 00:35:22.576
really surprised me.

00:35:22.976 --> 00:35:24.196
It came up when I was talking

00:35:24.286 --> 00:35:25.166
with Loic [phonetic], a type

00:35:25.216 --> 00:35:27.586
designer, and I asked him, "What

00:35:27.586 --> 00:35:29.986
helps you with your work?"

00:35:30.776 --> 00:35:32.056
>> So in the case of type

00:35:32.056 --> 00:35:33.236
design, for instance, we've

00:35:33.796 --> 00:35:35.656
developed all kinds of little

00:35:35.826 --> 00:35:36.906
drawing tricks.

00:35:36.906 --> 00:35:38.296
In type design especially,

00:35:38.886 --> 00:35:41.036
subjectiveness I feel can

00:35:41.036 --> 00:35:42.496
[inaudible] even more than in

00:35:42.496 --> 00:35:44.106
other aspects of design because

00:35:44.106 --> 00:35:46.706
we go to the depth of how the

00:35:46.706 --> 00:35:48.196
particular curve of, on the

00:35:48.196 --> 00:35:50.366
shoulder of a lowercase m is,

00:35:50.366 --> 00:35:50.916
for instance.

00:35:50.916 --> 00:35:52.566
And we can have a 10-minute

00:35:52.566 --> 00:35:54.906
discussion only on that.

00:35:55.046 --> 00:35:56.496
But the difficult part is

00:35:56.596 --> 00:35:59.596
describing what you see in words

00:35:59.596 --> 00:36:01.286
that the other person is going

00:36:01.286 --> 00:36:03.006
to understand the way you mean

00:36:03.006 --> 00:36:05.036
it, and that's very difficult

00:36:05.036 --> 00:36:06.106
when you're talking about shape.

00:36:06.696 --> 00:36:08.976
But one way we started doing

00:36:08.976 --> 00:36:10.266
that with some of my colleagues

00:36:10.266 --> 00:36:12.386
was basically redrawing the

00:36:12.386 --> 00:36:14.076
shape we're looking at with

00:36:14.076 --> 00:36:16.566
exaggerated features, where we

00:36:16.566 --> 00:36:18.406
basically kind of make a

00:36:18.406 --> 00:36:19.676
caricature of what we are

00:36:19.676 --> 00:36:20.156
seeing.

00:36:20.886 --> 00:36:22.916
So if I'm pushing what I'm

00:36:22.916 --> 00:36:25.366
seeing to the extreme of why I

00:36:25.476 --> 00:36:27.966
find it ugly or uncomfortable,

00:36:28.256 --> 00:36:30.456
it's because it feels like that

00:36:30.456 --> 00:36:30.696
to me.

00:36:31.536 --> 00:36:32.616
And through that drawing,

00:36:32.616 --> 00:36:33.876
usually the other people can

00:36:33.876 --> 00:36:36.076
start seeing that much more

00:36:36.076 --> 00:36:38.506
toned down but existing feature

00:36:38.506 --> 00:36:40.116
of the design that they weren't

00:36:40.116 --> 00:36:41.616
necessarily perceiving before

00:36:41.616 --> 00:36:42.906
because that's not what they

00:36:42.906 --> 00:36:44.386
were looking at.

00:36:44.486 --> 00:36:46.086
So it is about trying to make

00:36:46.086 --> 00:36:48.466
people see the world through

00:36:48.526 --> 00:36:50.416
your eyes and the other way

00:36:50.476 --> 00:36:52.206
around, like gaining the ability

00:36:52.206 --> 00:36:53.206
to see the world through their

00:36:53.206 --> 00:36:55.686
eyes, so that you can then find

00:36:55.686 --> 00:36:56.926
that third place that is

00:36:56.926 --> 00:37:00.906
actually the joint gaze that you

00:37:00.906 --> 00:37:01.696
have on the world.

00:37:02.086 --> 00:37:04.916
And that's the, that I think to

00:37:04.916 --> 00:37:07.016
me is the key of a successful

00:37:07.016 --> 00:37:08.756
collaboration in design is

00:37:08.756 --> 00:37:13.656
finding that place.

00:37:13.886 --> 00:37:15.946
>> Wow. Before we even dig into

00:37:15.946 --> 00:37:17.826
this technique, have you thought

00:37:17.896 --> 00:37:19.076
about type design?

00:37:19.436 --> 00:37:20.896
I mean, every single letter that

00:37:20.956 --> 00:37:22.956
you text, and email, and that

00:37:22.956 --> 00:37:24.696
you read, that's been designed,

00:37:25.546 --> 00:37:27.666
and type designers care so much

00:37:27.706 --> 00:37:29.336
about detail that they've

00:37:29.336 --> 00:37:31.176
invented ways to communicate

00:37:31.176 --> 00:37:33.256
about shape when there are no

00:37:33.256 --> 00:37:33.696
words.

00:37:34.586 --> 00:37:35.736
That's just so cool.

00:37:36.776 --> 00:37:38.446
So to Loic's point, when you're

00:37:38.446 --> 00:37:40.226
designing for others, it's

00:37:40.366 --> 00:37:42.016
really necessary to see the

00:37:42.016 --> 00:37:44.046
world through their eyes, and

00:37:44.126 --> 00:37:45.546
this technique helps achieve

00:37:46.596 --> 00:37:46.686
that.

00:37:46.846 --> 00:37:50.256
So draw caricatures and ask

00:37:50.256 --> 00:37:51.456
others to do the same.

00:37:52.196 --> 00:37:53.416
It's really the importance of

00:37:53.416 --> 00:37:54.636
putting yourself in others'

00:37:54.636 --> 00:37:56.276
shoes because you can better

00:37:56.276 --> 00:37:57.496
understand their world.

00:37:58.126 --> 00:37:59.686
And this is a great tool for

00:37:59.686 --> 00:38:01.786
communication if words are not

00:38:01.866 --> 00:38:03.306
doing it, and it'll help you

00:38:03.306 --> 00:38:04.546
understand what others are

00:38:04.546 --> 00:38:04.986
seeing.

00:38:05.526 --> 00:38:08.416
This next technique is going to

00:38:08.416 --> 00:38:10.236
be unveiled through a story.

00:38:10.916 --> 00:38:13.236
Actually, even better, a first

00:38:13.446 --> 00:38:14.426
job story.

00:38:15.176 --> 00:38:17.226
Because you learn a lot on your

00:38:17.226 --> 00:38:19.286
first job, and they have a huge

00:38:19.286 --> 00:38:19.616
impact.

00:38:20.716 --> 00:38:22.356
So I asked my colleague Doug

00:38:22.496 --> 00:38:24.106
what he learned at his first

00:38:24.286 --> 00:38:24.946
design job.

00:38:25.526 --> 00:38:30.296
>> One of the real kind of ahas

00:38:30.296 --> 00:38:33.406
for me was a question that I got

00:38:33.406 --> 00:38:35.196
at the Tech Museum from the Head

00:38:35.196 --> 00:38:37.546
of Design that was essentially,

00:38:37.936 --> 00:38:39.056
why is this good?

00:38:39.566 --> 00:38:41.166
Why is this thing that you just

00:38:41.166 --> 00:38:42.376
gave me good?

00:38:42.816 --> 00:38:45.486
And, you know, my initial

00:38:45.486 --> 00:38:47.276
reaction was, well, because I

00:38:47.346 --> 00:38:49.366
think this will be easy for

00:38:49.366 --> 00:38:50.316
people to do.

00:38:50.546 --> 00:38:53.326
And, you know, he responded,

00:38:53.326 --> 00:38:54.406
like, well, how do you know

00:38:54.406 --> 00:38:54.576
that?

00:38:54.796 --> 00:38:55.966
How do you know that this is

00:38:55.966 --> 00:38:57.666
going to be easier than the way

00:38:57.666 --> 00:38:58.486
that we do it now?

00:38:58.896 --> 00:39:01.946
And I kind of realized that I

00:39:01.946 --> 00:39:03.446
didn't know the answer to that.

00:39:03.446 --> 00:39:05.056
And then, I realized what he was

00:39:05.056 --> 00:39:07.716
really asking is, should we put

00:39:07.716 --> 00:39:10.046
all of this energy into making

00:39:10.046 --> 00:39:11.816
the changes that you're

00:39:11.816 --> 00:39:12.756
suggesting?

00:39:13.236 --> 00:39:14.546
How can we be sure that that's

00:39:14.546 --> 00:39:15.696
the right thing to do?

00:39:15.926 --> 00:39:18.756
And to answer that question, I

00:39:19.416 --> 00:39:21.306
opened up -- it might have been

00:39:21.306 --> 00:39:23.656
Microsoft Paint [laughs] -- and

00:39:23.656 --> 00:39:27.136
I drew a picture, and I took it

00:39:27.136 --> 00:39:29.706
out onto the museum floor, and

00:39:29.806 --> 00:39:32.756
basically asked visitors to give

00:39:32.756 --> 00:39:35.176
me their impression of what they

00:39:35.376 --> 00:39:37.446
thought they should do based on

00:39:37.706 --> 00:39:39.176
kind of how I had arranged

00:39:39.176 --> 00:39:40.136
things on the screen.

00:39:41.606 --> 00:39:42.816
>> So what Doug was talking

00:39:42.816 --> 00:39:44.146
about here, and he went on to

00:39:44.226 --> 00:39:46.596
explain, that it was this method

00:39:46.596 --> 00:39:48.736
of prototyping that helped him

00:39:48.736 --> 00:39:50.026
answer that question from his

00:39:50.076 --> 00:39:50.376
boss.

00:39:51.206 --> 00:39:53.156
Why should we put energy into

00:39:53.156 --> 00:39:53.786
your idea?

00:39:54.736 --> 00:39:56.156
So what Doug learned at his

00:39:56.276 --> 00:39:58.196
first design job was that he

00:39:58.226 --> 00:40:00.096
could not assume that his

00:40:00.096 --> 00:40:01.236
designs were going to work.

00:40:01.236 --> 00:40:03.476
And this actually also came up

00:40:03.476 --> 00:40:05.106
in my conversation with Gary.

00:40:06.606 --> 00:40:07.666
>> It wasn't just designed on

00:40:07.666 --> 00:40:10.306
paper, implemented in code, and

00:40:10.306 --> 00:40:13.046
sort of assumed that that was

00:40:13.046 --> 00:40:13.336
going to work.

00:40:13.336 --> 00:40:15.906
You can't just assume from your

00:40:15.906 --> 00:40:18.266
own experience and through

00:40:18.476 --> 00:40:19.756
chatting that something's going

00:40:19.756 --> 00:40:20.006
to work.

00:40:20.006 --> 00:40:20.766
You've really got to go out and

00:40:20.766 --> 00:40:20.956
try it.

00:40:23.106 --> 00:40:24.236
>> And I think this is the part

00:40:24.236 --> 00:40:25.886
that's really important not to

00:40:25.886 --> 00:40:26.326
overlook.

00:40:27.516 --> 00:40:28.616
You know, in this case, we are

00:40:28.616 --> 00:40:30.296
talking about trying designs in

00:40:30.296 --> 00:40:32.906
context out in the real world to

00:40:32.906 --> 00:40:35.186
vet solutions to problems, and

00:40:35.186 --> 00:40:36.706
trying solutions is something

00:40:36.706 --> 00:40:37.956
that Sam mentioned too.

00:40:39.486 --> 00:40:42.196
>> One of our ethos's is to

00:40:42.196 --> 00:40:43.086
solve a problem.

00:40:43.286 --> 00:40:45.196
Put it in front of players and

00:40:45.306 --> 00:40:46.416
see how they react.

00:40:46.486 --> 00:40:47.316
See if they're learning what

00:40:47.316 --> 00:40:47.976
they need to learn.

00:40:47.976 --> 00:40:49.706
And if we need to do more, we'll

00:40:49.706 --> 00:40:50.146
do more.

00:40:50.686 --> 00:40:53.386
It's impossible to rush the

00:40:53.386 --> 00:40:55.216
creative process of making a

00:40:55.216 --> 00:40:57.496
game because so much of what's

00:40:57.496 --> 00:40:58.846
special about the games that you

00:40:58.846 --> 00:41:01.726
remember are decisions that seem

00:41:01.866 --> 00:41:03.456
very obvious and very small but

00:41:03.456 --> 00:41:05.616
take a really, really long time

00:41:05.616 --> 00:41:06.786
to arrive at.

00:41:06.786 --> 00:41:08.486
And you can't hire more people

00:41:08.486 --> 00:41:09.406
to get there faster.

00:41:09.406 --> 00:41:12.006
You just have to sit with it and

00:41:12.006 --> 00:41:13.866
continue working on it until the

00:41:13.866 --> 00:41:14.976
best solutions arise.

00:41:17.276 --> 00:41:18.886
>> So Sam said something here

00:41:18.886 --> 00:41:20.176
that I want to expand on.

00:41:21.196 --> 00:41:22.856
More people are not going to fix

00:41:22.906 --> 00:41:24.176
a creative problem.

00:41:24.666 --> 00:41:26.906
Great artists are patient.

00:41:27.456 --> 00:41:29.326
Sometimes you just get writer's

00:41:29.436 --> 00:41:30.856
block and there's no amount of

00:41:30.896 --> 00:41:32.296
conversation that's going to fix

00:41:32.296 --> 00:41:34.856
it, so you have to wait and just

00:41:34.856 --> 00:41:36.326
let that creative process

00:41:36.326 --> 00:41:36.846
happen.

00:41:37.356 --> 00:41:38.506
And that's okay.

00:41:38.986 --> 00:41:41.206
It's a part of the process, and

00:41:41.206 --> 00:41:42.866
sometimes that's exactly what is

00:41:42.866 --> 00:41:44.586
needed to produce quality.

00:41:44.876 --> 00:41:47.336
So the theme really from these

00:41:47.416 --> 00:41:49.976
last 3 clips is to go out and

00:41:50.136 --> 00:41:52.626
try your designs in context with

00:41:52.626 --> 00:41:53.376
real people.

00:41:54.086 --> 00:41:55.926
Show people prototypes and learn

00:41:55.926 --> 00:41:56.556
from their feedback.

00:41:57.376 --> 00:41:58.696
This is a really essential

00:41:58.796 --> 00:42:00.646
technique to help work through

00:42:00.646 --> 00:42:01.866
your design decisions.

00:42:01.866 --> 00:42:05.306
So we can learn a lot from each

00:42:05.306 --> 00:42:07.356
other, so I wanted to know what

00:42:07.356 --> 00:42:09.506
advice would one designer give

00:42:09.666 --> 00:42:10.686
to another designer.

00:42:11.336 --> 00:42:14.656
>> Learn how to accept, and

00:42:14.776 --> 00:42:16.296
sort, and prioritize the

00:42:16.296 --> 00:42:17.846
feedback as it comes in, whether

00:42:17.846 --> 00:42:19.036
it's from yourself or from

00:42:19.036 --> 00:42:19.336
others.

00:42:19.906 --> 00:42:21.116
You will learn so much more

00:42:21.116 --> 00:42:22.226
quickly than if you are

00:42:22.226 --> 00:42:23.966
defensive and you just, like,

00:42:23.966 --> 00:42:24.616
buckle down.

00:42:26.496 --> 00:42:27.666
>> I personally struggle with

00:42:27.706 --> 00:42:28.526
this.

00:42:28.616 --> 00:42:30.266
I can almost not help becoming

00:42:30.266 --> 00:42:32.326
defensive when I hear feedback

00:42:32.356 --> 00:42:33.406
on a project I'm working on.

00:42:33.406 --> 00:42:35.286
It's like this instinctual

00:42:35.286 --> 00:42:37.326
reaction, especially if I just

00:42:37.356 --> 00:42:38.956
spent late nights and weekends

00:42:38.956 --> 00:42:40.026
working on something.

00:42:41.066 --> 00:42:43.406
But still, I know it's

00:42:43.406 --> 00:42:46.216
important, but I wanted to know

00:42:46.216 --> 00:42:46.556
why.

00:42:46.736 --> 00:42:49.596
Again, why is it important to be

00:42:49.646 --> 00:42:50.676
open to feedback?

00:42:52.646 --> 00:42:53.966
>> I think there's also just a

00:42:53.966 --> 00:42:55.206
reality, which is after you've

00:42:55.206 --> 00:42:57.126
used your own work for some

00:42:57.126 --> 00:42:58.716
amount of time, you naturally

00:42:58.716 --> 00:43:00.396
develop some blind spots.

00:43:00.396 --> 00:43:01.966
And that's where having a really

00:43:01.966 --> 00:43:03.166
great, collaborative team and

00:43:03.166 --> 00:43:04.916
people that you trust around you

00:43:04.916 --> 00:43:06.986
to help critique your work is a

00:43:07.026 --> 00:43:07.896
really important part of the

00:43:07.896 --> 00:43:09.126
design process.

00:43:09.336 --> 00:43:10.406
So you can get fresh eyes on

00:43:10.406 --> 00:43:11.926
stuff and trust that people have

00:43:12.166 --> 00:43:13.436
the good intentions and they're

00:43:13.566 --> 00:43:14.986
going to be able to give you

00:43:14.986 --> 00:43:16.006
great insights of how you can

00:43:16.006 --> 00:43:16.406
improve.

00:43:17.776 --> 00:43:18.276
>> Totally.

00:43:18.956 --> 00:43:19.646
I've been there.

00:43:19.646 --> 00:43:21.026
I've definitely been too close

00:43:21.026 --> 00:43:22.396
on a project and lost sight of a

00:43:22.396 --> 00:43:24.266
big picture or overlooked some

00:43:24.456 --> 00:43:24.756
detail.

00:43:25.236 --> 00:43:27.196
So by being open to feedback,

00:43:28.156 --> 00:43:30.286
it's really easy then to have

00:43:30.346 --> 00:43:32.596
someone else like your team or

00:43:32.596 --> 00:43:33.306
somebody that you asked a

00:43:33.306 --> 00:43:35.346
question to give you something,

00:43:35.346 --> 00:43:36.506
some piece of information that

00:43:36.506 --> 00:43:37.566
can help you improve your

00:43:37.566 --> 00:43:38.076
designs.

00:43:39.066 --> 00:43:40.546
And I really like that May-Li

00:43:40.646 --> 00:43:42.336
said this word, "trust," to

00:43:42.336 --> 00:43:43.746
trust the people around you.

00:43:44.836 --> 00:43:46.646
So be open to feedback.

00:43:47.396 --> 00:43:48.986
It makes everything better and

00:43:48.986 --> 00:43:50.816
just ups the overall quality of

00:43:50.846 --> 00:43:52.726
design in your work.

00:43:53.276 --> 00:43:55.876
So this next technique is more

00:43:55.876 --> 00:43:57.706
of a mindset, and it came up

00:43:57.756 --> 00:43:59.396
when I asked Cas, who works on

00:43:59.476 --> 00:44:01.626
platform patterns, "How do you

00:44:01.626 --> 00:44:03.506
approach designing for so many

00:44:03.556 --> 00:44:03.866
people?"

00:44:03.866 --> 00:44:06.876
>> Knowing what you don't know,

00:44:08.296 --> 00:44:08.696
in a way.

00:44:08.976 --> 00:44:12.286
What I mean is that if you're

00:44:12.286 --> 00:44:13.266
looking at these things or if

00:44:13.266 --> 00:44:14.346
you're designing for these

00:44:14.346 --> 00:44:15.396
things, obviously, you have

00:44:16.306 --> 00:44:19.046
ideas and ways of using a

00:44:19.046 --> 00:44:20.516
certain device or an app in your

00:44:20.516 --> 00:44:21.396
own way, in your own

00:44:21.396 --> 00:44:22.826
environment, in your own habits,

00:44:23.356 --> 00:44:24.856
and you might know a little bit

00:44:24.856 --> 00:44:26.266
about how your friends are using

00:44:26.336 --> 00:44:27.956
it, or how you've seen other

00:44:27.956 --> 00:44:29.296
people use it, or maybe feedback

00:44:29.296 --> 00:44:30.996
you're getting, but it's a

00:44:30.996 --> 00:44:32.426
really big world, and there's a

00:44:32.426 --> 00:44:34.516
lot of people out there, and

00:44:34.946 --> 00:44:35.876
they all have their own needs,

00:44:35.936 --> 00:44:38.076
their own habits, their own way

00:44:38.076 --> 00:44:39.356
of going through life.

00:44:39.356 --> 00:44:40.546
And so you have to be very

00:44:40.546 --> 00:44:42.766
mindful that how you think about

00:44:42.766 --> 00:44:43.926
things or your opinions are not

00:44:43.926 --> 00:44:45.506
always, first of all, correct

00:44:45.506 --> 00:44:48.896
ones, nor the only ones.

00:44:49.696 --> 00:44:50.916
>> I really like how Cas put

00:44:50.916 --> 00:44:53.146
this at the beginning -- know

00:44:53.196 --> 00:44:54.146
that you don't know.

00:44:54.986 --> 00:44:56.286
And he also used this word

00:44:56.286 --> 00:44:57.326
"modesty" through our

00:44:57.326 --> 00:44:58.176
conversation.

00:44:58.686 --> 00:45:00.156
To be unassuming when you're

00:45:00.156 --> 00:45:02.046
designing for so many people.

00:45:03.016 --> 00:45:05.376
And that is a really great

00:45:05.416 --> 00:45:06.646
headspace to be in when you're

00:45:06.646 --> 00:45:08.846
approaching design; to be modest

00:45:09.456 --> 00:45:10.686
and to be mindful.

00:45:11.316 --> 00:45:14.656
So how do you help keep people's

00:45:14.656 --> 00:45:16.606
experiences top of mind when

00:45:16.606 --> 00:45:17.246
you're designing?

00:45:17.906 --> 00:45:19.826
>> So in many ways, I just have

00:45:19.826 --> 00:45:21.966
to be skeptical and ask

00:45:21.966 --> 00:45:23.516
questions if the idea in front

00:45:23.516 --> 00:45:25.566
of me, is that going to work for

00:45:25.566 --> 00:45:27.266
someone in a wheelchair, for

00:45:27.266 --> 00:45:27.726
example?

00:45:27.726 --> 00:45:28.866
Is that going to work for

00:45:28.866 --> 00:45:33.086
someone that has never used this

00:45:33.086 --> 00:45:33.686
app before?

00:45:33.686 --> 00:45:36.476
Is it going to work for someone

00:45:36.476 --> 00:45:37.996
coming from a PC to a Mac?

00:45:37.996 --> 00:45:39.716
You just have to ask lots of

00:45:39.716 --> 00:45:41.756
questions, and it can just start

00:45:41.756 --> 00:45:43.206
people thinking about, oh, yeah,

00:45:43.206 --> 00:45:44.456
did I care enough to consider

00:45:44.456 --> 00:45:47.346
that aspect of it?

00:45:47.626 --> 00:45:49.816
>> Right. So this may seem

00:45:49.816 --> 00:45:51.996
really simple, but it's

00:45:51.996 --> 00:45:53.756
important to ask questions,

00:45:54.106 --> 00:45:55.236
especially from different

00:45:55.236 --> 00:45:55.956
perspectives.

00:45:56.466 --> 00:45:57.296
That's going to help you

00:45:57.296 --> 00:45:58.836
maintain quality throughout your

00:45:58.836 --> 00:46:00.366
work and keep those other

00:46:00.366 --> 00:46:02.706
people's experiences in mind.

00:46:03.636 --> 00:46:05.296
So design is a really

00:46:05.296 --> 00:46:06.936
collaborative process, and

00:46:06.936 --> 00:46:08.336
there's a lot that goes into

00:46:08.336 --> 00:46:09.706
making collaboration work.

00:46:10.396 --> 00:46:12.146
At one point or another, we're

00:46:12.146 --> 00:46:13.386
all going to start on a new

00:46:13.386 --> 00:46:15.636
project or a new team, so what

00:46:15.686 --> 00:46:17.806
helps make that process a little

00:46:17.806 --> 00:46:18.456
bit easier?

00:46:20.306 --> 00:46:21.006
>> I always like to set

00:46:21.306 --> 00:46:22.236
expectations upfront.

00:46:22.886 --> 00:46:24.666
I just say, hey, this is how I

00:46:24.736 --> 00:46:25.016
am.

00:46:25.576 --> 00:46:27.956
This is how I work.

00:46:28.006 --> 00:46:29.386
This is how I communicate.

00:46:29.386 --> 00:46:30.196
How do you work?

00:46:30.196 --> 00:46:31.356
How do you communicate?

00:46:31.356 --> 00:46:32.806
What's your preferred method of

00:46:32.866 --> 00:46:33.586
communication?

00:46:33.586 --> 00:46:36.076
And by the way, here's the goals

00:46:36.146 --> 00:46:38.126
that I think we are working

00:46:38.126 --> 00:46:38.516
toward.

00:46:38.866 --> 00:46:39.856
And here are the things that are

00:46:39.856 --> 00:46:40.566
important to me.

00:46:40.566 --> 00:46:42.246
And please share with me the

00:46:42.246 --> 00:46:43.186
same for you.

00:46:43.746 --> 00:46:45.396
And I'll always sort of say it

00:46:45.396 --> 00:46:46.666
with a caveat like, "We're going

00:46:46.666 --> 00:46:47.946
to get all this business out of

00:46:47.946 --> 00:46:48.836
the way, and we're going to

00:46:48.946 --> 00:46:52.826
speak very directly about it."

00:46:53.086 --> 00:46:55.666
>> I know for me, talking about

00:46:55.666 --> 00:46:56.896
communication can be awkward,

00:46:57.666 --> 00:46:59.056
but after I tried this

00:46:59.186 --> 00:47:00.686
technique, I learned that it

00:47:00.686 --> 00:47:03.316
helps avoid so much drama and

00:47:03.316 --> 00:47:04.016
confusion.

00:47:04.446 --> 00:47:06.866
So talk about communication,

00:47:07.566 --> 00:47:08.506
especially if you're working on

00:47:08.616 --> 00:47:08.986
teams.

00:47:09.626 --> 00:47:11.346
Work towards the same goal about

00:47:11.346 --> 00:47:12.556
creating something great.

00:47:14.026 --> 00:47:16.396
So really, these six techniques

00:47:16.796 --> 00:47:18.596
are all about caring about the

00:47:18.596 --> 00:47:20.596
other people and having tools to

00:47:20.676 --> 00:47:22.566
talk about it, and you have to

00:47:22.716 --> 00:47:24.056
care about other people and put

00:47:24.056 --> 00:47:24.956
yourself second.

00:47:25.766 --> 00:47:27.506
Be mindful of their lives and be

00:47:27.506 --> 00:47:29.816
modest about your own because we

00:47:29.816 --> 00:47:31.606
just learned you can't assume.

00:47:31.876 --> 00:47:33.216
You have to go out and try your

00:47:33.216 --> 00:47:35.166
designs through prototyping and

00:47:35.166 --> 00:47:36.826
also really remain open to

00:47:36.926 --> 00:47:37.476
feedback.

00:47:37.976 --> 00:47:39.256
That's essential to making

00:47:39.256 --> 00:47:42.586
progress in design because, as

00:47:42.586 --> 00:47:44.876
May-Li said, we all develop

00:47:44.956 --> 00:47:47.866
blind spots, and we're not only

00:47:47.866 --> 00:47:50.026
designing to make progress, but

00:47:50.026 --> 00:47:51.356
we want to get closer to

00:47:51.356 --> 00:47:52.886
reaching our own aspirations and

00:47:52.886 --> 00:47:53.446
our own goals.

00:47:54.146 --> 00:47:56.866
So these techniques are used by

00:47:57.016 --> 00:47:58.656
real designers that I talked to,

00:47:59.126 --> 00:48:00.876
and they help them go through

00:48:00.876 --> 00:48:02.176
the process of designing, and it

00:48:02.176 --> 00:48:03.566
makes their days a little bit

00:48:03.566 --> 00:48:05.836
easier, so I hope they can help

00:48:06.096 --> 00:48:06.936
you too.

00:48:07.856 --> 00:48:09.806
So after all of these

00:48:09.806 --> 00:48:11.956
interviews, I learned that

00:48:12.156 --> 00:48:14.636
quality is the result of time,

00:48:15.056 --> 00:48:16.326
effort, and care.

00:48:17.116 --> 00:48:19.316
It's considered, it's crafted,

00:48:19.686 --> 00:48:21.096
and it means something different

00:48:21.096 --> 00:48:21.906
to different people.

00:48:23.416 --> 00:48:24.976
I also learned that quality

00:48:24.976 --> 00:48:27.366
impacts our every day, that your

00:48:27.366 --> 00:48:29.076
intentions are truly felt.

00:48:29.956 --> 00:48:32.316
High quality evokes trust, and

00:48:32.316 --> 00:48:34.246
that's really important, as well

00:48:34.246 --> 00:48:36.786
as it has to be earned.

00:48:36.936 --> 00:48:38.416
It's also important to strive

00:48:38.416 --> 00:48:41.166
for simplicity, to aspire to be

00:48:41.296 --> 00:48:43.126
stunning, and design to be

00:48:43.246 --> 00:48:43.536
timeless.

00:48:44.446 --> 00:48:45.966
Just think about how your app or

00:48:45.966 --> 00:48:47.726
game can have a positive impact

00:48:47.926 --> 00:48:49.386
on people's lives.

00:48:49.936 --> 00:48:51.856
And finally, working towards

00:48:51.856 --> 00:48:53.116
quality is all about

00:48:53.216 --> 00:48:54.986
communication, collaboration,

00:48:55.076 --> 00:48:57.496
and understanding, especially

00:48:57.496 --> 00:48:58.866
understanding the people you are

00:48:58.866 --> 00:48:59.626
designing for.

00:49:00.906 --> 00:49:02.586
So really, quality is a

00:49:02.676 --> 00:49:03.166
principle.

00:49:03.166 --> 00:49:06.156
It is intentional, and it's

00:49:06.156 --> 00:49:07.326
something that you have to ask

00:49:07.326 --> 00:49:09.326
yourself, what does quality mean

00:49:09.326 --> 00:49:09.916
to you?

00:49:10.316 --> 00:49:11.506
And you need to know your

00:49:11.506 --> 00:49:14.196
interpretation to go forward, to

00:49:14.196 --> 00:49:16.486
put in that hard work that meets

00:49:16.486 --> 00:49:18.076
your expectations and hits your

00:49:18.076 --> 00:49:21.006
aspirations because, at the end

00:49:21.006 --> 00:49:23.046
of the day, you're not designing

00:49:23.046 --> 00:49:23.656
for you.

00:49:24.096 --> 00:49:25.676
You're designing for other

00:49:25.676 --> 00:49:27.226
people who are going to use your

00:49:27.566 --> 00:49:28.466
app or your game.

00:49:29.066 --> 00:49:30.846
So make great designs for them.

00:49:32.606 --> 00:49:34.176
Now, there are two important

00:49:34.176 --> 00:49:35.726
statements on quality in great

00:49:35.726 --> 00:49:37.856
design that stand alone.

00:49:38.616 --> 00:49:39.646
These are going to play back to

00:49:39.646 --> 00:49:41.536
back, and I hope each offers

00:49:41.536 --> 00:49:42.596
something different that you can

00:49:42.596 --> 00:49:44.396
take away from today.

00:49:45.396 --> 00:49:49.216
>> Sensing the human behind the

00:49:49.216 --> 00:49:51.626
experience I think is really an

00:49:52.036 --> 00:49:53.696
earmark of something great.

00:49:58.036 --> 00:50:01.096
>> A great design is going to be

00:50:01.096 --> 00:50:02.586
the product of tremendous amount

00:50:02.586 --> 00:50:04.666
of effort, and creativity, and

00:50:04.856 --> 00:50:07.316
skill, and [laughs] late nights.

00:50:07.476 --> 00:50:10.086
It's going to seem effortless,

00:50:10.186 --> 00:50:12.606
and it should hopefully recede

00:50:12.606 --> 00:50:14.146
in people's consciousness.

00:50:14.736 --> 00:50:16.906
And in a way, I think you're

00:50:16.906 --> 00:50:18.656
very aware of an interface which

00:50:18.656 --> 00:50:20.456
has been poorly designed, and

00:50:20.456 --> 00:50:21.706
you're not at all aware of an

00:50:21.706 --> 00:50:23.356
interface which has been well

00:50:23.356 --> 00:50:23.826
designed.

00:50:28.296 --> 00:50:29.546
>> So I talked to a lot of

00:50:29.546 --> 00:50:31.586
people, and I saved something

00:50:31.626 --> 00:50:33.446
special just for the end.

00:50:34.266 --> 00:50:35.856
Since I had the opportunity to

00:50:35.936 --> 00:50:37.026
talk to so many different

00:50:37.026 --> 00:50:39.566
designers, I had to ask them onw

00:50:39.936 --> 00:50:40.906
final question, and it's

00:50:40.906 --> 00:50:42.226
something that I've always

00:50:42.226 --> 00:50:45.036
wanted, wondered myself: What

00:50:45.676 --> 00:50:47.536
are designers' favorite colors?

00:50:50.896 --> 00:50:51.906
>> Oh, wow.

00:50:52.316 --> 00:50:53.916
>> My favorite color?

00:50:53.916 --> 00:50:55.716
>> I have to say--

00:50:55.916 --> 00:50:57.066
>> Is there such a thing?

00:50:57.066 --> 00:50:58.816
I don't think so.

00:50:58.896 --> 00:51:00.076
>> I would have said glitter,

00:51:00.076 --> 00:51:01.076
but it's not a color.

00:51:01.446 --> 00:51:02.436
>> One of the things that I

00:51:02.436 --> 00:51:04.496
really love is Tahitian blue.

00:51:04.616 --> 00:51:06.736
>> But colors to me are like

00:51:06.736 --> 00:51:09.006
moods, and I do not have the

00:51:09.006 --> 00:51:09.936
same mood every day.

00:51:09.936 --> 00:51:10.796
I don't think I even have the

00:51:10.796 --> 00:51:12.516
same mood every hour, so.

00:51:12.516 --> 00:51:13.436
>> I really like white.

00:51:14.236 --> 00:51:15.186
Is it really a color?

00:51:15.376 --> 00:51:16.366
I think that's one of the

00:51:16.366 --> 00:51:17.486
reasons why I like it.

00:51:17.486 --> 00:51:18.646
>> My favorite color has been

00:51:18.646 --> 00:51:19.046
amber.

00:51:19.556 --> 00:51:20.896
>> I mean, lately, it's been

00:51:20.896 --> 00:51:22.216
green for some reason.

00:51:22.216 --> 00:51:22.926
I don't know why.

00:51:23.026 --> 00:51:25.746
>> I got to go back on this

00:51:25.746 --> 00:51:26.046
answer.

00:51:26.046 --> 00:51:29.346
Oh, it's actually Pantone 347.

00:51:29.346 --> 00:51:30.856
>> My favorite color is blue.

00:51:31.376 --> 00:51:33.996
>> Like a happy blue, and blue

00:51:33.996 --> 00:51:35.566
is, like, always such a color of

00:51:35.566 --> 00:51:37.076
responsibility, which is, like,

00:51:37.426 --> 00:51:37.976
so me.

00:51:38.046 --> 00:51:39.806
>> But I just think it's, like,

00:51:39.806 --> 00:51:41.596
soft and friendly.

00:51:42.036 --> 00:51:44.886
And food that's pink tastes

00:51:44.886 --> 00:51:44.976
good.

00:51:45.066 --> 00:51:46.416
>> I'm going to go with red.

00:51:46.416 --> 00:51:47.506
>> Throw out a hex value.

00:51:47.506 --> 00:51:48.996
I don't have a favorite color.

